{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01LicGt9gUFgPLQzDNQJyzQm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me plan the architecture. The migration from Spring Boot to Jakarta EE means:\n\n1. **Runtime:** Use an embedded servlet container approach. Since the app uses JSF + JPA + CDI, I'll use **Payara Micro** or a **WAR deployed to a lightweight Jakarta EE container**. The cleanest approach for a Docker-based app is to package as a WAR and deploy to **WildFly** or **Payara**. However, the simplest approach is to keep using an embedded approach. Let me use **Payara Micro** as the embedded runtime since it provides full Jakarta EE support (CDI, JPA, JSF, JTA) out of the box.\n\nActually, the most practical approach: Build a WAR and deploy it on **Apache TomEE** (which is Tomcat + Jakarta EE) or **Payara Micro**. Let me go with a WAR on an application server in Docker.\n\nLet me start the migration now - I'll work on multiple files:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":856,"cache_read_input_tokens":41656,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":856,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":829},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5178e60b-6983-4b64-b8b8-e65cc691e770","uuid":"a69f33d3-d9db-45d6-a949-d0ff4768b86a"}
